A3: SPL Library Checkouts

Introduction

This dataset is an account of all of the checkouts for stories from the author Sarah J. Maas. Author Maas is known for many great romance and fantasy novels, so I am a fan of her works and wanted to look at the data over the past couple years of just her books. During Covid-19 there was a rise of this “Booktok” hashtag on the app Tiktok, many videos of people suggesting books for others to read. I have come across this hashtag multiple times during quarantine, most of the videos being romance or fantasy recommendations. I know that one series from Sarah J. Maas was heavily recommended on Tiktok, so I am looking at the data with questions surrounding the influence of Tiktok on book checkout numbers, and overall how quarantine affected fantasy and romance checkout numbers. Why am I curious about this in particular: many have used apps like Tiktok and read novels of fantasy, romance, or distopian genres as a means of escape during Covid qurantine times, I simply want to see if this is true for books from an author like Sarah J. Maas!

Summary Information

According to a couple of articles from multiple news sources (like the Guardian), Booktok, a hashtag page on the app Tiktok started and became trending after August 2020 when a person’s book recommendation Tiktok went viral. It has become a page of popular book recommendations (mostly romance) for people to find out about books. Sarah J. Maas’s books like A Court of Thorns and Roses have excelled in the romance category in terms of recommendations on Tiktok.

Looking at the data, we have to take into account the rise of eBooks from intense quaranting during the Covid pandemic (libraries and bookstores closed), the increased number of books read in general from people being stuck in quarantine, as well as the rise in demand for romance and fantasy novels (from recommendations on Tiktok). The average number of checkouts per item in the dataset is 17.6 and looking at the number of checkouts per year we got: 2012: 80 2013: 291 2014: 752 2015: 1553 2016: 2563 2017: 3405 2018: 4431 2019: 5595 2020: 6238 2021: 11212 2022: 18370 2023: 2141 (We are not looking at 2023 too much since the year is not over yet)

Looking at this data we can definitely see a steady increase each year, and a sharp increase (almost doubles from 2020 to 2021) which can imply the theories regarding Covid-19 and quarantine, as well as Tiktok. Looking more closely at 2020 after the month of August (when Booktok really kicked off), there is a steady increase in the numbers after those months. The month with the maximum eBook checkouts in 2020 was December, further proving the previous statement of the increase. Looking at the differences between ebooks and paper books, we find that the number of checkouts for regular books each year (from 2019 to 2021) goes from 1192 to 366 to 958 (differences calculated as: -826, 592). This suggests that the pandemic and quarantining had a significant effect on the number of checked out physical books (probably due to libraries and bookstores being closed, and people not wanting to or allowed to leave their homes). As for eBooks, the numbers (from 2019 to 2021) go from 4403 to 5872 to 10254 (differences calculated as: 1469, 4382). There is a definite increase between these years, suggesting that quarantine increased eBook purchases and pushed people to try out eBooks for the first time (and ending up using that method for traveling etc so forth due to its comfortability). It’s hard to say whether or not Tiktok really impacted these numbers, considering the popularity of some of Sarah’s novels, but one thing for sure we can tell from these calculations is that Covid-19 had a huge impact on the number of books people read as well as the use of eBooks.

The Dataset

This dataset focuses on checkouts of any Sarah J. Maas books from the Public Library in Seattle each month from the years 2012-2023. This dataset refreshes every month, published and collected by the Seattle Public Library (SPL). They take summary data from their catelogs on checked out books and history of those numbers. We have to take into account accessibility mainly, as some of her books were very popular and hard to get a hold of from libraries. This could lessen the number of checked out physical books if there were not many copies available, or if there was a long line to hold a book. This data set does not account for those that downloaded pdfs of the books off of a website, or those who borrowed the book from someone who already has it (example: borrowed book from sister’s collection to read). The dataset also does not precisely show the correlation with the rise of booktok on tiktok for book recommendations, but can give us an idea of how covid-19 quarantining contributed to the numbers. This data collection started April 2005, however we are only looking at Sarah J. Maas books, which starts during 2012. This data was probably collected to look at trends of eBooks versus physical books of different genres. With the rise of technology and its uses, it raises questions about the future of libraries, and this data helps visualize this transformation over the past decade.

Checkout Trends Over Time Chart

This chart shows the number of checkouts of Sarah J. Maas books over the years. This chart was included to show the correlation between the pandemic and social media apps with checkout trends. From this chart we can conclude that there is indeed a sharp increase in numbers after 2020 (when quarantine really started and #Booktok kicked off) and a decline in numbers after quarantine ended. This suggests that fantasy and romance novels were quite in demand during quarantine as a possible means of escape or way to spend time stuck inside.

Ebook vs Physical Book Trends Over Time Chart

This chart shows the number of checkouts for Ebooks vs Books over time. This chart was included to show the correlation between the pandemic and the increase of use of Ebooks. With the rise of technology and its uses its hard to precisely tell if the pandemic alone contributed to this increase, but it is still interesting to see in the chart below. This chart suggests that the number of physical books checked out stayed roughly the same, increasing slightly during quarantine (makes sense considering the amount of time people spent indoors), but ebooks mostly have shined during and throughout this whole pandemic with the sharp increase following 2020. Bar Plot

This Bar plot shows the different series/titles that Sarah J. Maas has written and the number of checkouts for these novels. The TOG (throne of glass) is a special side short stories series that I included separately. What is surprising looking at this graph is that the Court Series (ACOTAR) has fewer books than the Throne of Glass Series, yet has much more checkouts. This can support the theories of this report surrounding the increased demand of romance and fantasy books during Covid (ACOTAR is a fantasy romance series). This also further contributes to the theory surrounding Tiktok’s Booktok page influence, as ACOTAR is a popular series with its own hashtag on the app.
